{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489791"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:31:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:31:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"747"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/747"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.35,0.07,0.19,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"747"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99458"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/747"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"747"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81845"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"166"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"819"},{"type":"contributions","id":"856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29608"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99458"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man with long-standing ulcerative colitis, usually well maintained on mesalazine, is hospitalised with an episode of acute severe colitis. He is treated with intravenous fluids, hydrocortisone and blood transfusion to correct his anaemia; and daily abdominal X-rays are performed. A flexible sigmoidoscopy confirms a florid ulcerative colitis. His condition remains stable until the fourth day after admission, when his abdominal pain becomes worse. His blood pressure is 100/65 mmHg, pulse 108/min and temperature 38.8C. His abdomen is distended, with widespread tenderness, but no guarding. His haemoglobin is 110g/L (130-175), white cell count 16.8 x 109/L (4-11), albumin 30g/L (34-48). Radiologically, his transverse colon is now 9 cm diameter (7 cm on initial presentation) and there is no free gas.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue current plan of management","Start intravenous ciprofloxacin and metronidazole","Increase the dose of hydrocortisone","Start infliximab","Colectomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is developing systemic toxicity in the setting of megacolon and is deteriorating despite active medical intervention. Patients in this scenario require salvage therapy which can medical (high dose cyclosporin or infliximab), or surgical (\u003Cstrong\u003Ecolectomy\u003C/strong\u003E). Absolute indications for surgical therapy include presence of impending perforation, multi system organ dysfunction (likely in this patient from clinical condition and low haemoglobin and albumin indicating septic shock) or failed of medical salvage therapy. Therefore, the most appropriate answer is colectomy. Infliximab, antibiotics and steroids will continue to be part of the management but are not the most important. Continuing current management would be ineffective and life-threatening.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colectomy may be indicated for active, severe colitis which is failing to respond to conventional medications."],"references":["https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=inflammatory-bowel-disease\u0026guidelineName=Gastrointestinal#toc_d1e365Therapeutic Guidelines. Ulcerative colitis in adults. In: Gastrointestinal. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2024. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?topicfile=ulcerative-colitis-in-adults\u0026guidelineName=Gastrointestinal","Bohl, JL \u0026 Sobba, K 2015, \u2018 Indications and options for surgery in ulcerative colitis\u2019, Surgical Clinics of North America, vol. 95, no. 6, pp 1211-32.Bohl JL, Sobba K. Indications and options for surgery in ulcerative colitis. Surg Clin North Am. 2015;95(6):1211\u201332. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.suc.2015.08.010"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81845"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"747"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81845"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-20T21:12:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-20T21:12:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"747"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99458"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":